Dataset Imputation

#combine duplicated "others" category
levels(data$ethnicity) = gsub("others", "Others", levels(data$ethnicity))

#change outlier/typo? 383 in age column. Impossible age. Replace value of 383 with 38.
data$age[data$age == 383] = 38
summary(data$age) #max value is now 64
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   17.00   21.00   27.00   29.21   35.00   64.00       2
#change mispelled column names
colnames(data)[colnames(data)=="jundice"] = "jaundice"
colnames(data)[colnames(data)=="austim"] = "autism"
colnames(data)[colnames(data)=="contry_of_res"] = "country_of_res"
colnames(data)[colnames(data)=="Class/ASD"] = "Class_ASD"

#replace nas with mean in age column
data$age = na.aggregate(data$age, FUN=mean) 

#replace 95 nas with "Unknown" in both: ethnicity and relation 
data_clean = data %>% 
  mutate_if(is.factor, fct_explicit_na, na_level = 'Unknown')

#drop columns
data_clean = data_clean[ -c(16) ] #take out country_of_res column 
#too many factors 
data_clean = data_clean[ -c(17) ] #take out result column 
#result score is related to Class and would give our model the outcome of the target variable
data_clean = data_clean[ -c(17) ] #take out age_desc as it only had one level, all the same
#won't show/tell us anything as all are the same one

#set up one hot encoding aka dummy variables to make all columns numeric except for target
dummies = dummyVars(~ ., data = data_clean[, -18], fullRank = TRUE)
#output of predict is a matrix, change it to data frame
one_hot = data.frame(predict(dummies, newdata = data_clean))
#append the original target variable (factor)
one_hot$Class_ASD = data_clean$Class_ASD
str(one_hot)

Split Data into Train/Test (70/30)

set.seed(101)
train_split = sample(1:nrow(one_hot), nrow(one_hot)*0.7) #take 70% sample
train = one_hot[train_split, ]
test_without_y = subset(one_hot[-train_split, ], select= -Class_ASD)
test_with_y = one_hot[-train_split, ]$Class_ASD
class_var_training = one_hot[train_split,]$Class_ASD

                       number = 10,

auc_knn
## [1] 0.9945376
#auc = 0.9952998
plot(performance(out_knn, "tpr", "fpr"))
abline(0,1)

Here are the accuracy and AUC statistics for our model:

  1. The accuracy is 0.967 which is excellent. This % shows how often the model is correct. 100% is perfect.

  2. The AUC is 0.9952998 which is also excellent almost perfect. Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), defined as a plot of sensitivity (from our confusion matrix) as the y coordinate versus its 1-specificity (from our confusion matrix) aka false positive rate (FPR) as the x coordinate. AUC is area under this. AUC represents measure of separability and tells us how much the model is capable of distinguishing between classes. The higher the AUC, the better the model is at predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s for example. AUC ranges from 0 to 1 with .50 meaning the model has no class separation capacity.

#for loop to determine best number of trees using ntree
accu = rep(0,1000)
for (i in 1:1000) {
  set.seed(i)
  rand_for = randomForest(Class_ASD~ ., data=train, ntree=i)
  pred_loop = predict(rand_for, test_without_y)
  cm = confusionMatrix(pred_loop, test_with_y)
  
  accu[i] = cm[3]$overall[1]
}
accu

Here are the accuracy and AUC statistics for our model:

  1. The accuracy is 0.9575 which is good. This % shows how often the model is correct. 100% is perfect.

  2. The AUC is 0.9912348 which is excellent. Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), defined as a plot of sensitivity (from our confusion matrix) as the y coordinate versus its 1-specificity (from our confusion matrix) aka false positive rate (FPR) as the x coordinate. AUC is area under this. AUC represents measure of separability and tells us how much the model is capable of distinguishing between classes. The higher the AUC, the better the model is at predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s for example. AUC ranges from 0 to 1 with .50 meaning the model has no class separation capacity.

#bootstrap 100 samples and calculate the 95% CI and AUC using poly kernal
n = 100
accuracy = rep(0,n)
auc = rep(0,n)
for (i in 1:n) {
  set.seed(i+100)
  new_index = sample(c(1:length(one_hot$Class_ASD)), length(one_hot$Class_ASD), replace=TRUE)
  new_sample = one_hot[new_index,]
  split = sample.split(new_sample$Class_ASD, SplitRatio = 0.8)
  train = subset(new_sample, split==TRUE)
  test.x = subset(subset(new_sample, split==FALSE), select=-Class_ASD)
  test.y = subset(new_sample, split==FALSE)$Class_ASD
  
  svm_poly = train(Class_ASD~ ., data=train, method="svmPoly",
                   tuneLength = 1, scale=FALSE,
                   trControl= trainControl(method="repeatedcv",
                                           repeats = 5, 
                                           classProbs=TRUE))
  
  #accuracy
  pred = predict(svm_poly, test.x)
  c = confusionMatrix(pred, test.y)
  accuracy[i] = c[3]$overall[1]
  
  #auc
  pred = predict(svm_poly, test.x, type="prob")[,2]
  out = prediction(pred, test.y)
  auc[i] = performance(out, measure="auc")@y.values[[1]]
}
#95% ci for accuracy
#accuracy

accuracy.mean

#upper ci = 0.9342495

Model Selection: Lasso

Lasso coefficient variables can go/shrink to 0. In lasso we remove variables that end up as 0 because they did not explain anything in our model. We will keep variables where the coefficients are not equal to 0 and fit our models with those.

Here are the accuracy and AUC statistics for our model:

  1. The accuracy is 0.9764 which is very good. This % shows how often the model is correct. 100% is perfect.

  2. The AUC is 0.9961728 which is excellent. Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), defined as a plot of sensitivity (from our confusion matrix) as the y coordinate versus its 1-specificity (from our confusion matrix) aka false positive rate (FPR) as the x coordinate. AUC is area under this. AUC represents measure of separability and tells us how much the model is capable of distinguishing between classes. The higher the AUC, the better the model is at predicting 0s as 0s and 1s as 1s for example. AUC ranges from 0 to 1 with .50 meaning the model has no class separation capacity.

Conclusion

In evaluation of the predictions of all models, all predicted the target extremely well: before lasso the SVM polynomial kernal model performed best and after lasso the neural network performed best.

I conclude that the survey scores are statistically reliable predictors of the target variable.

100% accuracy is not common but possible. We obtained 100% possibly because of linearly separable data and no overlapping data points? Is there overfitting somehow: memorizing the training set or test and training data are too much alike? The high accuracy scores need to be further researched to determine if the data is truly highly separable or if something else in the data needs to be addressed and the models retrained.

This dataset is highly biased towards the ethnicity of white European. I recommended collecting a more balanced dataset in the future for more accurate and unbiased modeling.

I hypothesize that with further data collection and ML, the survey could indeed be an important aid to clinicians in diagnosing ASD and reducing healthcare costs. ML methods have proven this survey dataset to be useful in predicting the outcomes of the target.
